label: Alfred Tarski
AlfredTarski
items.comment: Alfred Tarski is, with KurtGodel, one of the founders of contemporary logic. His papers on the theory of truth and logical consequence, as well as his studies on axiomatic geometry, are commonly identified as the starting point of formal semantics and model theory. Born Alfred Teitelbaum in Russian-occupied Poland, he converted to Catholicism and changed his name to Tarski, apparently in an outburst of Polish nationalism following the Russian retreat in #$WorldWarI. Whatever the motive, the conversion did little to mollify the numerous anti-semites in Polish academia: Tarski wrote his seminal papers while teaching mathematics in high school. He later moved to the United States and had a distinguished career at the University of California, where his students included Solomon Feferman and Richard Montague.

A Theorem_Proposition attributed to ReverendThomasBayes that states an important relation between conditional and marginal probability distributions of random variables. It is formalized in CycL as: 
(implies
  (and
    (probability ?EVIDENCE ?E)
    (probability ?HYPOTHESIS ?H)
    (conditionalProbability ?HYPOTHESIS ?EVIDENCE ?E-GIVEN-H)
    (conditionalProbability ?EVIDENCE ?HYPOTHESIS ?H-GIVEN-E))
  (mathEquals ?H-GIVEN-E
    (QuotientFn
      (TimesFn ?E-GIVEN-H ?H) ?E))).

Because the structure of a conceptual work can change over time (though it has exactly one structure at any given time), AISForFn (like correspondingAIS) is a TemporallyQualifiableRelation. Cyc's knowledge about artifacts in normal conditions
ArtifactsInNormalConditionMt
items.comment: This mt assumes that any given Artifact is not broken, is not under construction, is not junked, and is not ``in mothballs''. In other words, ``it works'' or ``it may serve its intended function'' is assumed about any given element of Artifact. Objects which are typically parts of things are assumed to be connected to what they are typically part of (e.g. all car wheels are assumed to be attached to some car). These assumptions are what allows us to state things such as ``furniture is typically right side up'', or ``centerboards are attached to sailboats.'' without excessive qualifications. Note that assertions such as ``couches typically weight tens to hundreds of pounds'' are true regardless of whether they are in the junkyard, or partially disassembled. Therefore, assertions about typical furniture weights should go in a less restrictive microtheory such as ObjectPhysicalCharacteristicsMt.

items.comment: An expression of the form (ArgSentenceFn ATOM SENT) is used to pick out an instance of CycLSentence based on its appearance as the value of an argument in the (CycLObjectTypeFn CycLAtomicSentence) ATOM. Specifically, it is used to denote the CycLSentence SENT with regard to its being the value of an argument of the CycLAtomicSentence represented by ATOM. Although closely related to the syncategorematic 'function' Quote, the expression (ArgSentenceFn ATOM SENT) does not denote SENT per se. Instead, it refers to ATOM relativize to SENT. The primary utility of this function is for representing assertions about CycLSentences in a form that can be easily fed out to alternative representational systems that cannot support second-order representations. The contextualization of SENT relative to ATOM allows us to unambiguously refer to the elements of one CycLSentence, even if syntactically-identical elements appear in mulitple CycLSentences. NOTE: The first argument of this function is not quoted so that it is possible to use a term to denote ATOM without it being the case that the term is an actual sentence that has SENT as the value of one of its argument.

items.comment:
A syntactic function on CycL expressions. ApplyOperatorFn takes as its arguments a CycLOperator (q.v.) and one or more other CycLTerms, and returns the CycLFormula that is the syntactic result of applying that operator to those terms. (ApplyOperatorFn OP TERM1...TERMn) is the CycL formula (OP TERM1...TERMn) constructed by writing OP followed by TERM1...TERMn (in that order) and enclosing the result in a pair of parentheses. For example, ApplyOperatorFn maps the sequence of expressions <`loves', `Socrates', `Plato'> to the sentence `(loves Socrates Plato)'; or to put the point in pure CycL:

(equals (ApplyOperatorFn (Quote loves) (Quote Socrates) (Quote Plato)) (Quote (loves Socrates Plato))) .

Similarly, (ApplyOperatorFn (Quote MotherFn) (Quote Plato)) is the non-atomic term (Quote (MotherFn Plato)).

ApplyOperatorFn is similar to a concatenation function on sequences of CycL terms (where the first term is an operator). More precisely, (ApplyOperatorFn OP TERM1...TERMn) is the concatenation of the left-parenthesis, OP, TERM1, ..., TERMn, and the right-parenthesis (in that order).

As the above examples show, ApplyOperatorFn in effect enables us to "distribute" `Quote' (q.v.) over the component terms within a formula (and to do the reverse). By the same token, it enables us to "quantify into" quoted formulae. Thus, the sentence

(thereExists ?TERM (and (denotes ?TERM ?THING) (isa ?THING Philosopher) (isa (ApplyOperatorFn (Quote loves) ?TERM (Quote Plato)) CycLAssertion)))

means that there is some sentence of the form

(loves TERM Plato)

asserted in the Cyc Knowledge Base such that the term TERM used in that sentence denotes a philosopher; i.e. there is some philosopher such that it is asserted in the KB that s/he loves Plato.

But note that the terms used in an `ApplyOperatorFn'-based formula are _not_required_ to be CycLQuotedTerms (q.v.): any CycL expression that denotes a CycL term (or operator, in the case of the formula's first argument) can be used in such a formula.

Note also that the formula (OP TERM1...TERMn) returned by ApplyOperatorFn, while syntactically well-formed, is not guaranted to be "semantically well-formed". Thus, the arity of the Relation RELN denoted by OP might not be n; and the denotatum of a given TERMi might not satisfy the argument-type constraints (see ArgTypePredicate) on RELN's ith argument.
label: Apply Operator Fn
ApplyOperatorFn

In other words, (AggregateRoleFn ROLE) is a BinaryRolePredicate that relates a situation to the group consisting of all the situation participants which relate to it via ROLE. For example, consider a dishwashing event Dishwashing001 in which many dishes are washed. Each dish that is washed is an objectActedOn in Dishwashing001. Summer 1997.  Atta disappears from his university for over a year, giving only a vague explanation
     for his absence. Western intelligence has established that Atta traveled to Afghanistan,
     to the camps of Al Qaeda. He is followed by al-Shehhi and Jarrah.

items.comment: AttendingFn is a collection denoting function which takes as its argument a type of event and returns a collection of events, which collection is itself a collection of subevents of the instances of the subcollection of Event entered in the Arg1 position. For example, (AttendingFn EntertainmentEvent) returns the collection of events which consist of attending some entertainment event or other. Moreover, attending an entertainment event is a subevent of the entertainment event in question, which is itself an instance of EntertainmentEvent, so (AttendingFn EntertainmentEvent) is a collection of subevents of instances of EntertainmentEvent. Another more specific example would be (AttendingFn BalletDancePerformance), which would be the collection of all instances of attending an instance of ballet. Since attending a ballet is a subevent of an instance of ballet, (AttendingFn BalletDancePerformance) is a collection of subevents of instances of BalletDancePerformance. Yet a third example is as follows: (AttendingFn SocialGathering) returns the collection of events in which some agent attends some instance of SocialGathering. In each case, 'AttendingFn' is meant to distinguish the spectators from the performers, or the guests from the hosts.
